word_summaries_chapter_1:
  1:1:1:"The first word of verse (1:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">bi</i> is usually translated as \"with\" or \"by\". The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">sīn mīm wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">س م و</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  1:1:2:"The second word of verse (1:1) is a proper noun in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The proper noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām hā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ه</span>)."
  1:1:3:"The third word of verse (1:1) is a masculine singular adjective and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The adjective's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā ḥā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ح م</span>)."
  1:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (1:1) is a masculine singular adjective and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The adjective's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā ḥā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ح م</span>)."
  1:2:1:"The first word of verse (1:2) is a masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā mīm dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح م د</span>)."
  1:2:2:"The second word of verse (1:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and proper noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The proper noun is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The proper noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām hā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ه</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  1:2:3:"The third word of verse (1:2) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā bā bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ب ب</span>)."
  1:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (1:2) is a masculine plural noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn lām mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ل م</span>)."
  1:3:1:"The first word of verse (1:3) is a masculine singular adjective and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The adjective's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā ḥā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ح م</span>)."
  1:3:2:"The second word of verse (1:3) is a masculine singular adjective and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The adjective's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā ḥā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ح م</span>)."
  1:4:1:"The first word of verse (1:4) is a masculine active participle and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm lām kāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">م ل ك</span>)."
  1:4:2:"The second word of verse (1:4) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">yā wāw mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ي و م</span>)."
  1:4:3:"The third word of verse (1:4) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dāl yā nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">د ي ن</span>)."
  1:5:1:"The first word of verse (1:5) is a second person masculine singular personal pronoun."
  1:5:2:"The second word of verse (1:5) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is first person plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn bā dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ب د</span>)."
  1:5:3:"The third word of verse (1:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and personal pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The personal pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  1:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (1:5) is a form X imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is first person plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn wāw nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع و ن</span>)."
  1:6:1:"The first word of verse (1:6) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The imperative verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل أمر</span>) is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hā dāl yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ه د ي</span>). The attached object pronoun is first person plural."
  1:6:2:"The second word of verse (1:6) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād rā ṭā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص ر ط</span>)."
  1:6:3:"The third word of verse (1:6) is a form X masculine active participle and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf wāw mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق و م</span>)."
  1:7:1:"The first word of verse (1:7) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād rā ṭā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص ر ط</span>)."
  1:7:2:"The second word of verse (1:7) is a masculine plural relative pronoun."
  1:7:3:"The third word of verse (1:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn ʿayn mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ع م</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">التاء</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  1:7:4:"The fourth word of verse (1:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and object pronoun. The attached object pronoun is third person masculine plural. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  1:7:5:"The fifth word of verse (1:7) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ghayn yā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">غ ي ر</span>)."
  1:7:6:"The sixth word of verse (1:7) is a masculine passive participle and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The passive participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ghayn ḍād bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">غ ض ب</span>)."
  1:7:7:"The seventh word of verse (1:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and object pronoun. The attached object pronoun is third person masculine plural. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  1:7:8:"The eighth word of verse (1:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and negative particle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  1:7:9:"The ninth word of verse (1:7) is a masculine plural active participle and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḍād lām lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ض ل ل</span>)."